The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 17, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 16: The government today said it will come out with clarifications on the transaction tax on Monday. I will clarify the position on Monday, when I reply to the discussion on the budget, finance minister P. Chidambaram said in the Lok Sabha. At a post-budget meeting with apex chambers Ficci and the CII, Chidambaram had promised to have a relook at the transaction tax rate.																								 Mumbai, July 16: Colgate Palmolive India Ltd has posted a net profit of Rs 25.44 crore for the quarter ended June 30, 2004 compared with Rs 20.69 crore for the quarter ended June 30, 2003. The board has declared a first interim dividend of 15 per cent for the year ending March 31, 2005 payable on or about July 23, the company has informed the BSE.																								 Mumbai, July 16: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) today said the capital market intermediaries should use unique indentification number for all secondary capital market transactions from August 2.																								 New Delhi, July 16: NDTV today reported a net profit of Rs 7.6 crore for the quarter ended June 30 against a loss of Rs 20.5 crore in the corresponding period last year. NDTVs consolidated income shot up 437 per cent to Rs 40.5 crore against Rs 7.5 crore in the year-ago period.																								 Mumbai, July 16: The rupee closed at 45.96 per dollar, a sharp recovery of nearly 11 paise from Thursdays 22-day closing low of 46.11. The RBI intervened through heavy dollar sales by state-run banks to arrest a four-session steep slide that sent the rupee tumbling to over three-week lows.																								 New Delhi, July 16: Software and services export revenue is estimated to have grown 28 per cent in dollar terms to $12.2 billion in 2003-04 with IT-enabled services showing a growth of 54 per cent during the same time. 																								 London, July 16: British American Tobacco said the Chinese government approved a plan for a manufacturing joint venture, enabling it to expand in the worlds largest cigarette market.
